docs.abstract: Organizers and demonstrators say they feel safer communicating with end-to-end encryption.
docs.snippet: Organizers and demonstrators say they feel safer communicating with end-to-end encryption.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over the last two weeks, the number of Americans who have downloaded Signal, an encrypted messaging application, has skyrocketed. Many are using the app to organize and participate in protests against police brutality (without being spied on by law enforcement).

headline.main: Signal Downloads Are Way Up Since the Protests Began
headline.print_headline: Messaging App Gains A Foothold in Protests

docs.abstract: “The violence that’s affecting black trans women and black trans folks is finally getting the attention that it deserves,” an organizer of the Brooklyn march said.
docs.snippet: “The violence that’s affecting black trans women and black trans folks is finally getting the attention that it deserves,” an organizer of the Brooklyn march said.
docs.lead_paragraph: West Dakota, a drag queen in Brooklyn, was checking in on a fellow drag queen and mentor when they began discussing what they said was a painful reality about the George Floyd protests: Black transgender people are disproportionately the victims of police violence, but attending demonstrations against police brutality can often put them in further danger.

headline.main: How a March for Black Trans Lives Became a Huge Event
headline.print_headline: Transgender Rights Rally Ended Up as a Huge Event

docs.abstract: Jill Snyder says she is stepping down “to advance the movement for change that is now sweeping through our culture.”
docs.snippet: Jill Snyder says she is stepping down “to advance the movement for change that is now sweeping through our culture.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Jill Snyder, who has served as director of the Museum of Contemporary Art Cleveland for 23 years, resigned on Friday, the museum said in a statement, “to begin a transition to new leadership” for the contemporary art institution. Her departure comes nearly two weeks after Ms. Snyder publicly apologized to an artist for canceling his exhibition dealing with police killings of black and Latino boys and men.

headline.main: MoCA Cleveland Director Resigns After Canceling Show on Police Brutality

docs.abstract: Some are reconsidering the rules surrounding protests and demonstrations on and off the field.
docs.snippet: Some are reconsidering the rules surrounding protests and demonstrations on and off the field.
docs.lead_paragraph: After Colin Kaepernick and other athletes caused a stir in 2016 by kneeling for the national anthem to protest racism and police brutality, leagues scrambled to set policies on such demonstrations. Now, in the wake of the killing of George Floyd and the nationwide protests it inspired, the issue may well arise again as American sports return. And some leagues are revisiting their rules.

headline.main: How Sports Leagues Regulate Athletes’ Activism
headline.print_headline: The Rules on Activism They Are A-Changin’

docs.abstract: As thousands of protesters took to the streets over the past week, artists, both amateur and professional, created a vast collection of drawings, paintings and illustrations in support of the protests and the Black Lives Matter movement.
docs.snippet: As thousands of protesters took to the streets over the past week, artists, both amateur and professional, created a vast collection of drawings, paintings and illustrations in support of the protests and the Black Lives Matter movement.
docs.lead_paragraph: Thousands of people have taken to the streets over the last week to protest police brutality and systemic racism, sparking a movement that has inspired hundreds of demonstrations across the country and ushered in a new wave of themed art.

headline.main: ‘The World is on Fire:’ Artists Respond to the Protests

byline.original: By Antonio de Luca and Jaspal Riyait

docs.abstract: “We shouldn’t be screaming, ‘Trans Lives Matter,’ but we have to,” said Leiomy Maldonado, a ballroom icon. “We’re strong and we’re here to fight.”
docs.snippet: “We shouldn’t be screaming, ‘Trans Lives Matter,’ but we have to,” said Leiomy Maldonado, a ballroom icon. “We’re strong and we’re here to fight.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Earlier this year, videos emerged of members of the ballroom community voguing in hazmat suits, holding “kiki” battles via TikTok and creating hand washing tutorials with new coronavirus-inspired beats and chants. Then came the videos of members cat walking with protesters, dropping into “dips” in front of police cars, voguing at impromptu protest balls and marching the asphalt runway while holding Black Lives Matter signs.

docs.abstract: Amid a backlash and an ad boycott, “Tucker Carlson Tonight” is still attracting big audiences, another sign of the nation’s political divide.
docs.snippet: Amid a backlash and an ad boycott, “Tucker Carlson Tonight” is still attracting big audiences, another sign of the nation’s political divide.
docs.lead_paragraph: In recent weeks, Tucker Carlson, the conservative Fox News host, has challenged the Black Lives Matter movement, dismissed demonstrators as “criminal mobs,” accused a Texas police chief of “sounding more like a therapist than a cop” and mocked a CNN children’s special about racism that featured Elmo, the “Sesame Street” puppet.

headline.main: Advertisers Are Fleeing Tucker Carlson. Fox News Viewers Have Stayed.
headline.print_headline: Ads May Flee Carlson, But Viewers Stay Put

byline.original: By Michael M. Grynbaum and Tiffany Hsu

docs.abstract: The organization filed the suit on behalf of a reporter who said he was hit in the face with a projectile shot by the police as he was covering a protest.
docs.snippet: The organization filed the suit on behalf of a reporter who said he was hit in the face with a projectile shot by the police as he was covering a protest.
docs.lead_paragraph: Dozens of journalists covering the nationwide protests against racism and police brutality have said they were attacked, arrested, intimidated with weapons or shot with nonlethal projectiles while doing their jobs.

headline.main: A.C.L.U. Sues Minneapolis, Claiming Police Tactics Violated Freedom of Press
headline.print_headline: A.C.L.U. Sues Minneapolis For Attacks On Reporters

docs.abstract: State supreme court judges are starting to grapple publicly with the racial injustices in the criminal justice systems they oversee.
docs.snippet: State supreme court judges are starting to grapple publicly with the racial injustices in the criminal justice systems they oversee.
docs.lead_paragraph: If after reading the 10th (or 50th) pledge of corporate solidarity with the anti-police brutality protests your eyes are hurting from rolling so much, you’re not alone. Nike? Check. Netflix? Check. Peloton? Check. The revolution has been focus-grouped.

headline.main: ‘We Are Part of the Problem They Protest’

docs.abstract: The day marks the anniversary of when slaves in Galveston, Texas, first learned of their freedom on June 19, 1865.
docs.snippet: The day marks the anniversary of when slaves in Galveston, Texas, first learned of their freedom on June 19, 1865.
docs.lead_paragraph: Twitter and Square on Tuesday designated Juneteenth, which celebrates the end of slavery in America, as a company holiday — the latest conciliatory overtures by major corporations since the widespread protests over police brutality and the death of George Floyd.

headline.main: Twitter and Square Make Juneteenth a Company Holiday
